{"type":"message","id":"debb1f8f","parentId":"3119be9f","timestamp":"2026-04-18T09:36:34.330Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Deciding on commits**\n\nI see the repo has a lot of unrelated changes. I want to commit only the files we've changed, so I need to check if git recognizes 20260418_hypotheses.md as untracked. It appears untracked, so it might not have been committed before. We modified it, and I’m considering committing just three relevant files, maybe skipping the generated context file since it doesn’t seem necessary. However, I’m weighing whether to include the report because we edited it. Prioritizing the script and template seems wiser.\n\n**Evaluating commit choices**\n\nI'm considering whether to keep the file uncommitted since it already exists. We've updated it to a safer state, but perhaps committing the generated report could make sense. However, it might be clearer to commit just the deterministic template and script to avoid clutter. The user might want the current report saved, which we've already corrected. I think I can stage the script and template, and maybe include the current report, even though being untracked could complicate commit history. We’ll commit the source changes and note that the report was corrected locally.\n\n**Committing source changes**\n\nI’m weighing whether to ensure a clean commit. With unrelated changes, it seems I can only commit our source changes and the template while leaving the report local. However, the instruction to \"commit your changes\" could apply to our edits, including the report. I need to check if daily reports are typically committed, and given there are many tracked, it seems likely. So, I think I'll go ahead and commit all three files. Let’s stage those specific files and complete the commit!","thinkingSignature":"{\"id\":\"rs_0fad9e409c19087f0169e3509495f4819a98c4d4e1fa63e93b\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp41Cga07xSe51k8isv2KsR